{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489272"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:11:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:11:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"622"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/622"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.24,0.12,0.02,0.54]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"622"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52901"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/622"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"622"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38290"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1328"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"192"},{"type":"contributions","id":"217"},{"type":"contributions","id":"257"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14986"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18394"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42115"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52901"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the Cardiology clinic for assessment. He has a medical history of dilated cardiomyopathy with a left ventricular ejection fraction of 25%. His regular medications include furosemide, enalapril, metoprolol controlled release, digoxin, spironolactone, atorvastatin, metformin and salbutamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. History and examination suggest he has New York Heart Association (NYHA) Class III heart failure. His electrocardiogram demonstrates sinus rhythm with a prolonged QRS duration of 140 ms. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate modification to his regular medication regimen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Addition of aspirin","Change digoxin to verapamil","Change metoprolol controlled release to atenolol","Addition of warfarin","Change enalapril to sacubitril/valsartan"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptomatic heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF), currently on guideline-directed medical therapy. The most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Echange enalapril to sacubitril/valsartan\u003C/strong\u003E. Sacubitril/valsartan, an angiotensin receptor-neprilysin inhibitor (ARNI), has been shown to improve mortality and reduce hospitalizations in patients with NYHA Class II-IV heart failure with reduced ejection fraction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe PARADIGM-HF trial demonstrated the superiority of sacubitril/valsartan over enalapril in reducing the risks of death and hospitalization for heart failure in patients with HFrEF. Neprilysin inhibition increases levels of endogenous vasoactive peptides, countering the neurohormonal overactivation in heart failure. When switching from an ACE inhibitor to sacubitril/valsartan, a 36-hour washout period is necessary to avoid angioedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAddition of aspirin\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this patient as there is no mention of coronary artery disease. Aspirin has no proven benefit in heart failure without concomitant ischemic heart disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanging digoxin to verapamil\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate. Calcium channel blockers like verapamil are generally contraindicated in severe left ventricular systolic dysfunction due to their negative inotropic effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanging metoprolol controlled release to atenolol\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended. Metoprolol CR has proven benefits in heart failure with reduced ejection fraction, while atenolol does not have the same evidence base for this indication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAddition of warfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate next step. While warfarin may have a role in reducing stroke risk in severe systolic dysfunction, it does not improve systolic function or quality of life. Moreover, this patient is in sinus rhythm, and there\u0027s no indication for anticoagulation based on the information provided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, changing enalapril to sacubitril/valsartan is the most appropriate modification to this patient\u0027s medication regimen, as it offers the best potential for improving outcomes in symptomatic heart failure with reduced ejection fraction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sacubitril/valsartan is recommended for patients with NYHA Class II-IV heart failure with reduced ejection fraction to improve mortality and reduce hospitalizations.","When switching from an ACE inhibitor to sacubitril/valsartan, a 36-hour washout period is necessary to avoid angioedema.","Beta-blockers with proven benefit in heart failure (e.g. metoprolol CR) should not be changed to those without evidence (e.g. atenolol)."],"references":["McMurray J, Packer M, Desai A, Gong J, Lefkowitz M, Rizkala A et al. Angiotensin\u2013Neprilysin Inhibition versus Enalapril in Heart Failure. New England Journal of Medicine. 2014;371(11):993-1004.","Follath F, Cleland J, Klein W, Murphy R. Etiology and response to drug treatment in heart failure. Journal of the American College of Cardiology. 1998;32(5):1167-1172.","Hjalmarson \u00c5, Goldstein S, Fagerberg B, Wedel H, Waagstein F, Kjekshus J et al. Effects of Controlled-Release Metoprolol on Total Mortality, Hospitalizations, and Well-being in Patients With Heart Failure. JAMA. 2000;283(10):1295.","Abdo A, Kemp R, Barham J, Geraci S. Dilated Cardiomyopathy and Role of Antithrombotic Therapy. The American Journal of the Medical Sciences. 2010;339(6):557-560"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38290"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"622"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38290"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-11T21:06:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-11T21:07:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"622"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52901"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCo